
     <p>2025.07.13 : <a href="https://ndpr.nd.edu/reviews/seeing-more-kants-theory-of-imagination/" >View this Review Online</a> | <a href="https://ndpr.nd.edu//news" >View Recent NDPR Reviews</a></p>
     <p><strong><p><strong>Samantha Matherne, <em>Seeing More: Kant’s Theory of Imagination</em>, Oxford University Press 2024, 448pp., $135.00 (hbk), ISBN 9780198898283.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Wiebke Deimling, Clark University</strong></p>
     <p><em>Seeing More</em> answers two questions. What is the imagination for Kant? And what role does it play in his philosophical picture? It is named for the reading Samantha Matherne proposes: the imagination is a capacity to “see more” than what is immediately given (109f.). This capacity is woven through our lives: we use it in simple perception, in appreciating beauty and sublimity, and in fulfilling our moral obligations.</p> <p>The book’s undertaking is difficult. It is unclear whether “imagination” has the same meaning across Kant’s corpus. Further, the imagination is difficult to locate in Kant’s taxonomy of mental faculties. Does it belong to sensibility or to the understanding? Does it belong squarely to the faculty of cognition as opposed to the faculties of feeling and desire?...
